prcitem.para: This functions is performed by a specific part, which is active in the FMGEC 1 only (FMGEC 2 also has a FIDS part, but an inactive one), and implemented with a specific board housing specific processor, I/O and memory media.
The FIDS gathers all the maintenance information from all the AFS computers, and then supplies this information to the CMS on the maintenance bus.
Display and interrogation of FIDS functions are done by selecting appropriate control on the MCDU.
A FIDS monitoring function has to be implemented.

In order to perform critical functions for FG, and to get a good level of confidence in FE computations, these parts include two independent computation channels with duplicated I/O circuits, central processor units, memories, power supplies and different unsynchronized clocks for each channel.
Command and monitor channels are physically segregated and programs of the computation are dissimilar.

Crosstalks between both lanes are achieved through ARINC 429 lines and through some hardware discretes. This data exchange is used for monitoring purposes and for transferring parameters that are acquired or computed by only one lane. Within each lane, all processors (except FIDS) are synchronized, thus reducing parameter transport delays.

Some basic rules about FMGEC architecture can be established: all operational functions are performed by Software, and only a few safety critical items such as part of the engagement logic are implemented in hardware.

The FE part of each lane processes most of the FE and FG, including common FM/FG and FM/FE ARINC inputs, thus avoiding the repeated performance of an identical ARINC processing inside a given lane, providing FE and FG processor with a balanced computation load and also keeping FE functions available in case of a specific FG or FM failure.
Within each lane, data are exchanged between FE and FG through common memory.

Likewise, the FM function communicates with the FG part by a common memory. The FM part is located in Command Lane, and performed by three processing units (specific FM I/O processing, main processor, data base processor).
The FE, FG and FM parts are independent from each other from both the hardware and software points of view.
AFS FIDS is performed by a separate processing unit, active in FMGEC 1, and I/O are exchanged through ARINC buses.

topic.title: How to use the Detailed Parts List

prcitem.para: The Detailed Parts List contains one or more figures which show the main assemblies of the equipment. Details of the parts are given on the opposite and subsequent pages.
The list is divided into these columns:

unlitem.para: 1st column: Figure Item − Figure and Item number
2nd column: Part Number − Manufacturer"s Part Number
3rd column: Airline Stock Number
4th column: Nomenclature
5th column: Effectivity Code
6th column: Units per assy − Quantity for the next higher assembly.

prcitem.para: The figure number is given on the first line at the top of each page. Each item in the parts list which has a part number also has an item number. If there is a dash in front of an item number, the item is not shown on the figure. A letter before the item number refers to the figure which shows a variant of the related part. A letter after the item number identifies a variant of the part.

Each assembly, subassembly and detail part has a manufacturer"s Part Number (if it is shown on the figures or not). If the Part Number has more than 15 characters, the data in this column is given for identification only. The full manufacturer"s Part Number is given in the NOMENCLATURE column, after the indication "ORDER OVERLGTH MPN...". It is followed by the FSCM (Federal Supply Code for Manufacturer).
This column is for airline use.

The NOMENCLATURE column gives the names of the assemblies and parts. The indication "ATTACHING PARTS" shows the parts which attach an assembly or part. These attaching parts are given directly below the assembly or part they attach. The next line has three asterisks, the first of which is directly below the item which is attached.

A Vendor Code is given for all the items which do not have a prime manufacturer"s Part Number. This Vendor Code is given at the right of the NOMENCLATURE column. The addresses and codes of Vendors are given in the VENDOR CODE LIST. Optional Part Numbers and Vendors are given in the OPTIONAL PARTS LIST in the IPL. Please note that only the manufacturers who appear in the OPL have been accepted as a result of the equipment qualification test, and should therefore be used.

If a part can come from a range of possible parts, the indication "SEL FROM" is given below the part. The indication "ESDS" is given in the NOMENCLATURE column for electronic components which are sensitive to electrostatic discharges.
The Effectivity Code is a letter which shows the interchangeability of the parts on a figure, as shown below:

unlitem.para: The detail part with item number 10A can only be installed in the unit with item number 1A.
The detail part with item number 10B can be installed in units 1A, 1B and 1C.
The detail part with item number 10C can only be installed in unit 1D.
The subassembly with item number 20A can only be installed in unit 1A.
The subassembly with item number 20B can be installed in units 1A, 1B and 1C.
The subassemblies with item numbers 20C and 20D and their attaching parts 30A can be installed in all the units with item number 1. Thus, they do not have an effectivity code.
The detail part with item number 40A can only be installed in the subassembly with item number 20A.
The detail part with item number 40B can be installed in subassemblies 20A, and 20B.
The detail part with item number 40C can be installed in subassemblies 20A, 20B and 20C.
The detail part with item number 40D can only be installed in subassembly 20D.

prcitem.para: The UNITS PER ASSY column shows the number of parts necessary for the next higher assembly. For some assemblies or parts, the number is replaced by the letters RF (forTEST REFEXT Reference) and AR (As Required).
